SCORING FRAMEWORK — 6 DIMENSIONS
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

Score each dimension 0–100. Use the full range. Be differentiated.
Reference specific numbers in every evidence field.
If data is missing, score 0 and state explicitly what is missing.

─────────────────────────────────────────
DIMENSION 1: BUSINESS QUALITY (0–100)
─────────────────────────────────────────
Assess the structural quality of the business model. Use your web search findings here.

→ What is the actual competitive moat? (brand, switching costs, network effects, IP, regulatory, scale)
→ Gross margin: absolute level vs sector norms, and multi-year trend (expanding/stable/contracting)
→ Operating leverage: does revenue growth drop through to EBIT disproportionately?
→ Revenue growth: multi-year CAGR, not just YoY — is growth consistent or lumpy?
→ NI growing faster than revenue = margin expansion = pricing power evidence
→ What does your research reveal about competitive dynamics and moat durability?

Calibration:
  91–100  Rare — GM 70%+, 20%+ CAGR, clear margin expansion, verified durable moat
  76–90   Excellent — GM 50–70%, 12–20% CAGR, stable/expanding margins, identifiable moat
  61–75   Good — GM 30–50%, 8–12% CAGR, broadly stable, some competitive advantage
  41–60   Average — GM 20–30%, 3–8% growth, mixed margin trend, limited differentiation
  21–40   Below average — GM < 20%, slow/declining growth, or margin contraction
  0–20    Structurally challenged — negative margins, declining revenue, commoditised

─────────────────────────────────────────
DIMENSION 2: UNIT ECONOMICS & CASH GENERATION (0–100)
─────────────────────────────────────────
Assess whether reported earnings are backed by real cash. This is the quality check.

→ FCF/Net Income ratio — the single most important check (< 0.7x raises serious concerns)
→ FCF yield — free cash flow as % of market cap
→ Capex/Revenue — < 5% asset-light; 5–10% moderate; > 15% capital-intensive
→ Is FCF growing faster than revenue? (operating leverage flowing to cash)
→ Any divergence between operating cash flow and net income?

Calibration:
  91–100  FCF/NI > 1.1x, FCF yield > 7%, capex/rev < 5%, FCF growing faster than revenue
  76–90   FCF/NI > 0.9x, FCF yield > 5%, low capex, clean cash conversion
  61–75   FCF/NI > 0.75x, FCF yield > 3%, manageable capex
  41–60   FCF/NI 0.5–0.75x, FCF yield 1–3%, moderate capex
  21–40   FCF below NI, high capex, or FCF yield < 1%
  0–20    Negative FCF, FCF/NI < 0.5x, or data entirely missing

─────────────────────────────────────────
DIMENSION 3: RETURNS ON CAPITAL (0–100)
─────────────────────────────────────────
ROIC is the single most predictive metric of long-term value creation.

→ ROIC level: compare to estimated WACC (assume 8–10% for most businesses)
→ ROIC trend: improving = moat widening; declining = competitive erosion
→ ROIC consistency: volatile ROIC signals cyclicality or execution risk
→ ROE cross-check: if ROE >> ROIC, leverage is driving returns (not economic quality)
→ For growing companies: is incremental capital deployed at high returns?

Calibration:
  91–100  ROIC > 30% sustained, improving trend, strongly above cost of capital
  76–90   ROIC 20–30%, stable or improving, strong spread over WACC
  61–75   ROIC 12–20%, stable, meaningful spread over WACC
  41–60   ROIC 7–12%, minimal spread over WACC
  21–40   ROIC 3–7%, close to cost of capital, limited value creation
  0–20    ROIC < 3%, negative, or no data

─────────────────────────────────────────
DIMENSION 4: GROWTH QUALITY & COMPOUNDING TRACK RECORD (0–100)
─────────────────────────────────────────
THIS IS THE MOST CRITICAL DIMENSION FOR IDENTIFYING GENUINE COMPOUNDERS.

A consistent 15% grower for 5 years >> a 30% one-year grower followed by declines.
Consistency is the primary differentiator. Compute it rigorously.

→ Revenue CAGR across full available period (not just YoY)
→ NI CAGR vs revenue CAGR — NI CAGR > Rev CAGR = margin expansion = moat evidence
→ Growth consistency: compute each year's growth rate and assess variance
   Low variance (all years within ±5pp of mean) = high quality
   High variance (years ranging from -10% to +40%) = low quality, lumpy, cyclical
→ Growth trajectory: most recent rate above or below historical average?
   Accelerating = positive; decelerating = scrutinise carefully
→ Down years: any year with negative revenue growth = significant penalty
→ Your research: is this growth organic or acquisition-driven?

Calibration:
  91–100  Revenue CAGR 20%+, NI CAGR > Rev CAGR, near-zero variance, no down years
  76–90   Revenue CAGR 12–20%, NI CAGR > Rev CAGR, low variance, no down years
  61–75   Revenue CAGR 8–12%, positive NI expansion, moderate consistency
  41–60   Revenue CAGR 4–8%, NI roughly in line, some year-to-year variation
  21–40   Revenue CAGR < 4%, significant variance, or 1–2 down years
  0–20    Revenue declining overall, multiple down years, or highly volatile

─────────────────────────────────────────
DIMENSION 5: BALANCE SHEET STRENGTH (0–100)
─────────────────────────────────────────
A strong balance sheet is optionality. A leveraged one is a constraint.

→ Net debt position: net cash (negative net debt) is the gold standard
→ Net Debt/EBITDA — primary leverage metric
→ Interest coverage: EBIT / interest (> 10x comfortable; < 3x concerning)
→ Balance sheet trajectory: leverage increasing or decreasing?
→ Goodwill as % of total assets: > 50% signals acquisition-heavy, intangible-heavy risk

Calibration:
  91–100  Fortress — net cash, zero leverage, full financial optionality
  76–90   Strong — leverage < 0.5x ND/EBITDA, substantial flexibility
  61–75   Good — 0.5–1.5x ND/EBITDA, comfortable coverage
  41–60   Adequate — 1.5–2.5x ND/EBITDA, manageable but limits flexibility
  21–40   Stretched — 2.5–4x ND/EBITDA or goodwill-heavy
  0–20    Distressed — > 4x leverage, covenant risk, or negative equity signals

─────────────────────────────────────────
DIMENSION 6: PHOENICIAN CAPITAL FIT (0–100)
─────────────────────────────────────────
Holistic judgment synthesising all five dimensions + portfolio context + your research.
This is your overall conviction score as a senior analyst.

→ Portfolio comparison: how does this compare to what Phoenician already owns?
   Is it additive (new geography, new sector) or duplicative?
   Is it a higher or lower quality version of an existing holding?
→ Owner alignment: founder-led signals, CEO tenure, insider ownership
→ Moat durability: what does your research reveal about competitive position sustainability?
→ Scalability: can this grow 5–10x without proportional capital reinvestment?
→ Information edge: genuinely under-followed? ($250M–$2B, limited sell-side coverage)
→ Valuation: given ROIC and growth, is the current multiple attractive, fair, or stretched?
   Key heuristic: EV/EBIT ÷ ROIC = "price per unit of return"
   < 1.0x = potentially cheap; 1.5–2.0x = fair; > 2.5x = expensive
→ Red flags from your research: governance, customer concentration, key-person risk

Calibration:
  91–100  Must investigate immediately — rare, all criteria firing, portfolio-additive
  76–90   High conviction — strong compounder, one or two manageable concerns
  61–75   Interesting — quality business, worth deeper research, some gaps
  41–60   Marginal — interesting but insufficient differentiation for Phoenician
  21–40   Weak fit — below Phoenician's quality or growth standards
  0–20    No fit — fundamentally incompatible with mandate

